<h1>
  A Safer Dose <span>Written in the Genome</span>
</h1>

<p class="hero-sub">
  A pharmacogenomics story about drug response, precision medicine,
  and why the same medication may not work the same way for every person.
</p>

<div class="story-image">
  <img
    src="/pharmacogenomics-drug-response.png"
    alt="Pharmacogenomics illustration showing DNA, medication, and individualized drug response"
  >

  <p class="credit">
    Illustration: PanorOmics original visual concept for pharmacogenomics and individualized drug response.
  </p>

  <p class="image-explain">
    The image shows a medicine placed between DNA and human profiles, representing how genetic variation can influence drug response, dose requirements, and treatment monitoring.
  </p>
</div>

<section class="section">

  <h2>
    The <span>Human Story</span>
  </h2>

  <p>
    Two patients may receive the same medication, but their bodies may not process
    or respond to that medication in the same way. One person may break down a drug
    slowly and face a higher risk of side effects. Another may process it quickly
    and need closer monitoring to reach the intended therapeutic effect.
  </p>

  <p>
    Pharmacogenomics studies how genetic differences influence drug response.
    Instead of treating medication response as one-size-fits-all, pharmacogenomics
    asks a more precise question: can genomic information help guide safer and
    more individualized treatment decisions?
  </p>

</section>

<section class="section">

  <h2>
    Why <span>Genomics Matters</span>
  </h2>

  <p>
    Drug response can be shaped by genes involved in drug metabolism, drug targets,
    transport, immune reactions, and biological pathways. In some cases, genetic
    variation can help explain why people differ in dose requirements, treatment
    benefit, or risk of adverse reactions.
  </p>

  <p>
    Warfarin is one of the clearest examples often used to explain pharmacogenomics.
    Variants in genes such as <em>VKORC1</em> and <em>CYP2C9</em> can influence
    warfarin sensitivity and metabolism. Genetic information may support initial
    dose estimation, but clinical monitoring remains essential.
  </p>

</section>

<section class="section">

  <h2>
    The Omics <span>Connection</span>
  </h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Genomics:</strong> identifies inherited variants that may influence drug response.</li>
    <li><strong>Transcriptomics:</strong> can reveal how drug-response genes are expressed in tissues.</li>
    <li><strong>Proteomics:</strong> connects genetic variation to enzymes, receptors, and drug targets.</li>
    <li><strong>Metabolomics:</strong> helps measure biochemical changes after medication exposure.</li>
    <li><strong>Clinical data:</strong> connects molecular signals with outcomes, safety, and monitoring.</li>
  </ul>

</section>

<section class="section">

  <h2>
    What This Story <span>Teaches</span>
  </h2>

  <p>
    Pharmacogenomics does not mean that DNA alone makes every treatment decision.
    It means that genomic information can become one important layer in precision
    medicine, alongside clinical history, laboratory monitoring, age, weight,
    organ function, other medications, and physician judgment.
  </p>

  <p>
    The larger lesson is simple: precision medicine begins when biology becomes
    personal. A drug is not only a chemical compound; it enters a living system
    shaped by genes, proteins, metabolism, environment, and health history.
  </p>

</section>

